 for bestpractices and # Ticket Board

## Overview
Build a feature-rich, Kanban-style Ticket Board within LifeOps that enables teams to manage issues/tickets with dynamic agent automation rules, bulk edit capabilities, and sprint planning tools. This page sits at the core of Project Management Automation (roadmaps, ticketing automation, PR summarization, release notes, CI/CD integrations via agents) and is tightly integrated with the Project Detail view (backlog, roadmap items, tickets, PRs, agent-run history, and action widgets). The UI must be performant, accessible, and resilient to null/undefined data, with strong runtime safety guarantees as specified in the mandatory coding standards.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A comprehensive Kanban board for tickets within a project, featuring multiple lanes (columns) such as Backlog, Ready, In Progress, In Review, Done, and custom/status-based lanes.
- An Agent Automation Rules Panel to define and manage rules that triage, assign, tag, escalate, or auto-resolve tickets based on ticket attributes, events, or agent state.
- A Sprint Planner to allocate tickets to sprints, visualize capacity, and drag tickets into sprint columns; includes capacity indicators per sprint and per-team/resource constraints.
- Bulk Actions to perform multi-ticket edits (change status, assign, tag, priority, estimate, convert to tasks, bulk PR summarization notes, etc.).
- Tight integration with Roadmaps and CI/CD workflows via agents, enabling automated ticket routing to automation templates, PR summarization, release notes generation, and deployment steps.
- Auditability: every action is explainable, reversible, and logged with traceable agent messages, consistent with LifeOps governance.

How this page should look and behave:
- A dense yet readable Kanban board with draggable tickets between columns, inline quick-edit, and bulk operation controls.
- Left-hand side: collapsible navigation tree and filter panel for projects, teams, assignees, labels, and sprint contexts.
- Top header: project context, sprint selector, quick actions (Create Ticket, Create Automation Rule, Run Summary), search, and global filters.
- Right-side: Agent Automation Rules Panel with create/edit rule UI, preview of rule effects, and a history of rule executions.
- Sprint planner dock: an integrated panel showing active sprint(s), capacity, and a draggable area to assign cards to sprints.
- Cards: dark elevated with rounded corners, top-aligned priority icon or badge, title, assignees, tags, due date, and a compact bottom bar with status, points, and last updated times.
- Interactions: drag-and-drop tickets across columns; bulk select with a persistent action toolbar; modal dialogs for editing ticket details; in-place quick edits; confirm prompts for destructive bulk actions.
- Visual guidance: subtle depth, crisp typography, high contrast in action areas (e.g., bulk actions, critical status changes), and restrained accents per the design system.

## Components to Build
1) TicketBoardLayout
- Role: container wiring board, sprint planner, automation panel, and filters.
- Props: projectId, initialSprintId, userPermissions.
- State: boardColumns (with order and visibility), ticketsByColumn, selectedTicketIds, isBulkEditing, activeSprint, filters.
- Safeguards: ensure all arrays are initialized (useState<Type[]>([])). Use data ?? [] for fetch results.

2) KanbanColumn
- Props: id, title, tickets: Ticket[], onMoveTicket, onEditTicket, onBulkAction.
- Behavior: render ticket cards in a vertical lane; support drag-and-drop; show column capacity if applicable.

3) TicketCard
- Props: ticket: Ticket, onOpen, onInlineEdit, onBulkToggle, isSelected.
- UI: compact card with title, meta (assignee avatars, labels, due date, priority), and action menu (quick edit, convert, tag).

4) BulkActionsBar
- Props: selectedTicketIds: string[], onBulkApply(action), onClear.
- Features: bulk status change, assign, tag, convert, bulk PR/summary generation triggers.

5) AgentAutomationPanel
- Role: define, edit, and test automation rules for tickets.
- UI: list of rules with create/edit modal, rule builder (conditions, actions, scope), test runner, rule execution history.
- Data: rules per project; linked to tickets via attributes.

6) SprintPlanner
- Role: visualize sprints, capacity, and drag tickets into sprint columns.
- UI: sprint cards with capacity bars; sprint backlog panel; per-sprint action to lock/unlock.
- Interaction: drag tickets onto sprint columns; capacity validation.

7) ProjectDetailTimelinePanel
- Role: show agent-run history, rule executions, PR summaries, release notes, and artifacts.
- UI: collapsible sections with logs, diffs, and artifacts.

8) FiltersAndSearchBar
- Role: filter tickets by assignee, labels, priority, status, sprint, and text search.

9) APIBridge
- Centralized API adapters for Tickets, Sprints, Rules, Runs, Artifacts, and Agents. Implements safe access patterns.

10) DataModels and Types (TypeScript)
- Ticket, Rule, Sprint, Run, User, Label, Tag, Column, BoardState, etc.

Note: All components must guard against null/undefined before using array methods as per the runtime safety rules.

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Tech stack: React + TypeScript with a modern state management approach (React Context + useReducer or Zustand) for modularity and traceability.
- State initialization:
  - useState<Ticket[]>([]) and similar for all arrays.
  - Ensure all data fetch results use data ?? [] and Array.isArray checks before mapping.
- Drag-and-drop:
  - Use a robust DnD library (e.g., react-beautiful-dd or dnd-kit) with accessible semantics.
  - Validate moves: only allow moves that are permitted by rules (e.g., cannot move to a completed column if not allowed).
- Bulk editing and bulk actions:
  - Implement selection mechanism with bulk toolbar; ensure operations run on (selectedTickets ?? []) with guards.
- API integration points:
  - Fetch tickets, sprints, rules, runs, and artifacts; guard responses with Array.isArray and defaults.
  - Mutations: create/update tickets, create/edit rules, run automation tasks, publish PR summaries, generate release notes.
- Accessibility:
  - Keyboard navigable board, focus outlines, ARIA labels for drag-and-drop regions, live regions for status updates.
- Performance:
  - Virtualized rendering for large boards if needed; memoization of columns and tickets; debounce search/filter.

### Backend
- API endpoints (to support frontend needs):
  - GET /projects/{projectId}/tickets?filters
  - GET /projects/{projectId}/sprints
  - GET /projects/{projectId}/rules
  - POST /projects/{projectId}/rules
  - PATCH /tickets/{ticketId}
  - POST /tickets/bulk
  - POST /automation/run
  - POST /projects/{projectId}/roadmaps
  - GET /agents/runs?limit=...
  - GET /artifacts/{artifactId}
- Database models (SQL/NoSQL as per stack):
  - Tickets: id, title, description, status, assigneeId, priority, labels[], sprintId, estimate, storyPoints, createdAt, updatedAt
  - Columns: id, projectId, name, order, archived
  - Sprints: id, projectId, name, startDate, endDate, capacity, state
  - Rules: id, projectId, name, conditions JSON, actions JSON, enabled boolean, createdAt
  - Runs: id, ruleId or agentId, status, logs, artifacts
  - Artifacts: id, runId, type, contentRef
  - AuditLog: id, action, actorId, targetId, timestamp, details
- Validation:
  - All inputs must be schema-validated; server returns structured errors for client display.
- Security:
  - Authenticated access via OAuth/JWT; per-route authorization checks (project-scoped).
  - Audit trail enforcement for any mutate actions.

### Integration
- Data flow:
  - TicketBoard loads initial data (tickets, sprints, columns) using safe data access patterns.
  - SprintPlanner interacts with Sprint service for capacity; on drop, updates ticket.sprintId and revalidates capacity.
  - AgentAutomationPanel defines rules; on save, trigger validate and deploy to runtime, with run history captured in Runs.
  - BulkActionsBar composes updates via Tickets bulk endpoint; operations are batched and all successful or rolled back on error.
  - ProjectDetail interlocks: changes in tickets, rules, or sprints reflect in Roadmaps, PR summarization, and CI/CD pipelines as appropriate; ensure a consistent audit trail across modules.
- Data integrity:
  - Use data ?? [] for fetch results, Array.isArray checks prior to map/filter, destructuring with defaults, and nested optional chaining for deep responses.

## User Experience Flow
1) User navigates to LifeOps Project -> Ticket Board.
2) Board loads: columns rendered with current tickets, sprint context selected, and filters available.
3) User drags a ticket from Backlog to In Progress; system validates transition, updates ticket.status, and logs the action.
4) User selects multiple tickets (Shift/Ctrl/Meta) and applies Bulk Edit: change status, assign, add labels, or convert to tasks.
5) User opens an Agent Automation Rule panel to create a rule: define conditions (e.g., if ticket priority is High and assignee is Unassigned), actions (assign to API bot, add label, escalate), and schedule if needed.
6) User saves rule; rule is validated, deployed to runtime; a Run is recorded and available in the Agent Run history.
7) User opens Sprint Planner: views current sprint capacity, drags eligible tickets into the sprint; capacity is updated and a visual warning appears if over-commitment.
8) User uses PR summarization and release notes automation: select tickets/PRs, trigger summarization; generated artifacts appear in the Runs history and under Artifacts.
9) User navigates to Project Detail for a holistic view of backlog, roadmap items, tickets, PRs, and agent-run history; changes propagate here as appropriate.
10) All actions produce an audit log entry with reversible artifacts and explanations.

## Technical Specifications

Data Models: (TypeScript interfaces)
- Ticket { id: string; title: string; description?: string; status: string; assigneeId?: string; priority?: string; labels?: string[]; sprintId?: string; estimate?: number; storyPoints?: number; createdAt?: string; updatedAt?: string; }

- Column { id: string; projectId: string; name: string; order: number; archived?: boolean; }

- Sprint { id: string; projectId: string; name: string; startDate?: string; endDate?: string; capacity?: number; state?: string; }

- Rule { id: string; projectId: string; name: string; conditions?: any; actions?: any; enabled?: boolean; createdAt?: string; }

- Run { id: string; ruleOrAgentId: string; status: string; logs?: string[]; artifacts?: string[]; startedAt?: string; finishedAt?: string; }

- Artifact { id: string; runId: string; type: string; contentRef: string; }

- User { id: string; name: string; avatarUrl?: string; }

API Endpoints: (Examples; align to your routing)
- GET /api/projects/{projectId}/tickets
- GET /api/projects/{projectId}/sprints
- GET /api/projects/{projectId}/rules
- POST /api/projects/{projectId}/rules
- PATCH /api/tickets/{ticketId}
- POST /api/tickets/bulk
- POST /api/automation/run
- GET /api/projects/{projectId}/roadmaps
- GET /api/agents/runs
- GET /api/artifacts/{artifactId}

Security:
- OAuth2/JWT authentication; all routes require valid token.
- Project-scoped access control; verify user has permission to view/edit project.
- Audit trail: every mutating operation records actor, action, target, timestamp, and reversible payload.

Validation:
- Use schema validation on inputs; return precise error messages.
- Before mapping API results to UI, validate with Array.isArray and defaults; guard nested objects with optional chaining.

Destructuring with Defaults:
- Example: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {};

Optional Chaining:
- Use obj?.property?.nested when accessing API results.

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] The Ticket Board renders with at least 4 columns and loads tickets safely, with no runtime errors even if API returns null for arrays.
- [ ] All array operations guard against null/undefined: (data ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(data) ? data.map(...) : [] patterns.
- [ ] Bulk actions apply to all selected tickets and rollback cleanly on failure; UI shows a consolidated action status and per-ticket results.
- [ ] Drag-and-drop between columns updates server state and respects permission constraints; over-capacity warnings appear if sprint capacity is exceeded.
- [ ] Agent automation rules can be created/edited, and running a rule produces a Run entry with logs and artifacts captured.
- [ ] Sprint Planner correctly shows capacity and per-sprint dashboards; next-run time and last-run outcome are visible in Runs history.
- [ ] UI adheres to the visual style and design system, including color palette, typography, and spacing, with accessible contrast and focus states.
- [ ] All API responses are validated; missing data is gracefully handled with defaults and user-friendly messages.

## UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- Consistent color usage per the provided palette.
- Elevation, borders, and gradients align with the Card Design and Navigation rules.
- Typography adheres to hierarchy: headings, card titles, body text, microcopy.
- Layout follows 8px baseline grid with generous gutters; responsive breakpoints for tablets and desktops.
- Interactive elements exhibit consistent hover/focus behavior and micro-interactions.

